<paragraph id="B7727259FFF57215FF6CF562FB06F9E3" blockId="12.[151,1436,1117,1955]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FF6CF562FF57F86E" bold="true" box="[151,229,1117,1143]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Stems</emphasis>
1.1(0.1–3.0) m long, 7.4(4.0–11.0) cm diameter, solitary. 
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FC22F562FB87F86E" bold="true" box="[985,1077,1117,1143]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Leaves</emphasis>
12(8–19) per stem; sheaths 21.5(15.0–27.0) cm long; petioles 102.1(36.0–150.0) cm long; rachises 126.1(72.0–155.0) cm long, 8.8(6.1– 11.1) mm diameter; pinnae 6(5–8) per side of rachis; basal pinna 52.8(28.5–78.0) cm, long, 5.2(0.7–10.0) cm wide, angle with the rachis no data; apical pinna 42.4(32.5–49.5) cm long, 18.0(10.0–27.0) cm wide, forming an angle of 17(10–28)° with the rachis. 
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FD82F5C8FC9CF908" bold="true" box="[633,814,1271,1297]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Inflorescences</emphasis>
spicate, with a short peduncle, absent rachis, and 1 rachilla, this erect at anthesis; prophylls and peduncular bracts fibrous, covering all or part of the rachilla at anthesis; prophylls 15.2(11.5–18.5) cm long; peduncular bracts 20.2(19.0–22.5) cm long, inserted 3.3(2.0– 5.0) cm above the prophyll; peduncles 4.6(3.5–6.2) cm long, 10.0(8.2–13.5) mm diameter; rachilla 1, 13.6(11.5–15.5) cm long, 10.0(8.2–12.1) mm diameter; proximal lips of flower pits regularly shaped, rounded, completely covering pits before anthesis and not recurved; 
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FBF5F487FBEAF9CB" bold="true" box="[1038,1112,1464,1490]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">fruits</emphasis>
widely obovoid, without pronounced longitudinal ridges, 28.6(22.5–32.1) mm long, 20.8(18.1–24.5) mm diameter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B7727259FFF57215FF3DF739FDD7FA5E" blockId="12.[151,1436,1117,1955]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FF3DF739FDB6FA39" bold="true" box="[198,516,1542,1568]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Distribution and habitat</emphasis>
. From 8°34’– 
<geoCoordinate id="D2F9149EFFF57215FD4CF739FCBCFA39" box="[695,782,1542,1568]" degrees="9" direction="north" minutes="25" orientation="latitude" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" precision="925" value="9.416667">9°25’N</geoCoordinate>
and 78°48’– 
<geoCoordinate id="D2F9149EFFF57215FC49F739FBACFA39" box="[946,1054,1542,1568]" degrees="80" direction="west" minutes="56" orientation="longitude" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" precision="925" value="-80.933334">80°56’W</geoCoordinate>
in 
<collectingCountry id="CFDA32C9FFF57215FBA9F739FB1DFA39" box="[1106,1199,1542,1568]" name="Panama" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Panama</collectingCountry>
at 483(60–768) m elevation in lowland rainforest (
<figureCitation id="2FF66EDCFFF57215FDF6F712FDE7FA5E" box="[525,597,1581,1607]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="11.[151,255,1254,1278]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,205,1234]" captionTargetId="figure-248@11.[148,1434,200,1259]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distribution maps of Pholidostachys amazonensis, P. dactyloides, P. occidentalis, and P. panamensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894918/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B7727259FFF57215FF3DF76CFAB0FA8D" blockId="12.[151,1436,1117,1955]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FF3DF76CFE2AFA74" bold="true" box="[198,408,1619,1645]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="70CD09DAFFF57215FE5CF76BFD5EFA74" authorityName="Henderson" authorityYear="2012" box="[423,748,1620,1645]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="panamensis">
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FE5CF76BFD5EFA74" box="[423,748,1620,1645]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Pholidostachys panamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other species in its spicate inflorescences and widely obovoid fruits (
<figureCitation id="2FF66EDCFFF57215FE58F745FDB2FA8D" box="[419,512,1658,1684]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1097,1121]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1070]" captionTargetId="figure-318@8.[141,1445,169,1070]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. A. Fruits of Pholidostachys dactyloides (Dodson 14491). B. Fruits of P. occidentalis (Balslev 60678). C. Fruits of P. panamensis (Liesner 1255). D. Fruits of P. pulchra (de Nevers 4285). E. Fruits of P. sanluisensis (Juncosa 726). F. Fruits of P. synanthera subsp. synanthera (Couvreur 119). Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894916" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894916/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). See notes on 
<taxonomicName id="70CD09DAFFF57215FD4BF744FC53FA8D" authorityName="Wendl. ex Burret" authorityYear="1930" box="[688,993,1659,1684]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kalbreyeri">
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FD4BF744FC53FA8D" box="[688,993,1659,1684]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Pholidostachys kalbreyeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
under Excluded Names.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B7727259FFF57215FF3DF79FFCFAFB4F" blockId="12.[151,1436,1117,1955]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FF3DF79FFE7CFAA3" bold="true" box="[198,462,1696,1722]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Subspecific variation</emphasis>
. There are two separate populations of 
<taxonomicName id="70CD09DAFFF57215FC58F79EFB55FAA3" authorityName="Henderson" authorityYear="2012" box="[931,1255,1697,1722]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="panamensis">
<emphasis id="85B9AE4BFFF57215FC58F79EFB55FAA3" box="[931,1255,1697,1722]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Pholidostachys panamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, occurring 
<quantity id="7035DFBCFFF57215FA8BF79EFF0EFAFB" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="km" value="170.0">170 km</quantity>
apart in 
<collectingCountry id="CFDA32C9FFF57215FEDEF7F7FE34FAFB" box="[293,390,1736,1762]" name="Panama" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Panama</collectingCountry>
. Although sample size is small, the western population, on the eastern end of the Central Cordillera, has shorter stems, shorter petioles, and shorter and thinner basal pinnae than the eastern population, on the western end of the Serranía de San Blas. The western population also occurs at a higher mean elevation— 722(695–768) m versus 303(60–450) m.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B7727259FFF57215FF3DF65DFE49FBBA" blockId="12.[151,1436,1117,1955]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<bibRefCitation id="D35C0FA8FFF57215FF3DF65DFE25FB65" author="de Nevers, G." box="[198,407,1890,1916]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="329 - 342" refId="ref10968" refString="de Nevers, G. (1995) Notes on Panama palms. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences 48: 329 - 342." type="journal article" year="1995">de Nevers (1995)</bibRefCitation>
reported that some specimens have bifid inflorescences, but no such specimens have been seen in the present study.
</paragraph>
